Charger Families,
Due to the unhealthy air quality rating today in the Portland area we need to postpone today’s Supply Pick Up Event. We are hoping to reschedule for tomorrow afternoon from 4:00-7:00pm. If the air quality is still at an unhealthy level tomorrow, we will make a decision by noon to reschedule for next week.
Thanks for your understanding with this situation and we apologize for any inconvenience this may cause.
Take care.

This fall, while schools are engaged in distance learning, Parkrose Student Health Center is open 8:45 am-4:45 pm Monday for phone and video appointments only and 8:45 am-4:45 pm Tuesday-Friday for phone, video and in-person visits. Call 503-988-3392 to make an appointment.
Any Multnomah County K-12 youth can visit the center and there are no out of pocket costs. We also can connect students and their families with community resources for food or help with medical insurance.
Student Health Centers at David Douglas & Roosevelt are also open. For more information visit https://multco.us/health/student-health-centers. Stay connected with https://www.facebook.com/Multco.SBHC/ or
https://www.instagram.com/multco.studenthealth/

Multnomah County, Oregon
April 7 at 10:23 PM ·

Want to help older neighbors and those with disabilities during the COVID-19 crisis? There *are* some things you can do to help out while maintaining 6-feet of distance. The CDC also recommends wearing a face covering in public settings where social distancing is hard to maintain.*

✔️Check that food and medical needs are being met
✔️ Offer a grocery store or pharmacy run and
✔️ Check that your neighbor has social connection

If you see something is not right, call Multnomah County’s Aging and Disability Resource helpline at 503-988-3646 for 24-hour information.

And if you’re interested in volunteering or helping Multnomah County and the City of Portland respond to the COVID-19 outbreak visit: multco.us/donate-volunteer

*Please note, this video was recorded prior to CDC recommendations to wear masks or face coverings in public settings where social distancing measures are hard to maintain

As of last week, Oregonians who receive SNAP benefits can also order groceries online from Walmart and Amazon.

Multnomah County Student Health Centers
March 22 at 8:58 PM ·

Wondering what it means to "flatten the curve?" A public health expert explains: https://bit.ly/3d0PFi2

We can all work together to flatten the curve through social distancing, which includes:

• Canceling in-person classes at universities, colleges and schools

• Working from home whenever possible

• Avoiding crowds, shaking hands and being in close quarters with other people

• Avoiding public places except for essential activities such as grocery shopping or doctor’s appointments

post_text: Reminder: PHS Winter Arts Festival ~ TONIGHT, Monday, December 16th, 6:30pm-8:30pm
shared_text:
Parkrose School District
December 10, 2019 at 6:32 PM ·

PHS Winter Arts Festival ~ NEXT Monday, December 16th, 6:30pm-8:30pm
Admission is free. All proceeds from food, artwork sales, raffles, etc. will be equally divided between the PHS art departments.
Please join us in celebrating the work of the Parkrose High School Fine & Performing Art students.
"We are trying to create more opportunities to bring the Parkrose community together and create cohesion between all of the artists of the PHS student body." - Coral Worley, Co-President of Tri-M Music Honors Society
